This study explored the impact of an interactive, AI-generated error-correction strategy compared to standard AI self-learning with teacher summarization on student learning outcomes. Specifically, it investigated how these two distinct approaches influenced medical students' knowledge application and metacognitive skills within a biomedical materials course.

The study utilized a quasi-experimental, pre-test-post-test design involving an intervention group and a control group of undergraduate clinical medicine students. In the experimental condition, the interactive error-correction phase required student groups to input three teacher-recommended and two to three self-generated questions into an AI chatbot. The students then reviewed the AI-generated responses, identified factual errors or omissions, and used textbooks and reliable references to correct the inaccuracies before sharing their findings with the class.

- Significant Knowledge Application Gains: The error-correction learning method led to a significantly higher adjusted post-test mean score on the standardized knowledge application test for the intervention group compared to the control group ($87.57 \pm 6.50$ vs. $78.22 \pm 7.46$, $p < .001$).
    
- Elevated Metacognitive Awareness: Students in the intervention group demonstrated significantly higher overall metacognitive awareness scores ($4.14 \pm 0.58$) than those in the control group ($3.78 \pm 0.44$, $p < .001$).
    
- Subscale Competency Enhancements: The learning method produced positive impacts across all three evaluated dimensions of metacognition, yielding the largest improvement in metacognitive monitoring (Cohen's $d = 0.760$), followed by metacognitive knowledge (Cohen's $d = 0.667$) and metacognitive regulation (Cohen's $d = 0.473$).
    

The authors recommend that higher education shift toward a paradigm of "Learning with AI, Not from AI," explicitly incorporating structured pedagogical frameworks where AI is utilized as a fallible cognitive partner rather than an authoritative source. They advise integrating similar peer-driven error-correction strategies into competency-based curricula to cultivate critical evaluation and responsible AI utilization.
